Section1.Para:
The doping of transition metals in perovskite materials produces new magnetic and electronic structures with diverse properties. SrRuO3 (SRO), a metallic itinerant ferromagnet (FM), has attracted considerable interest because of its high thermal conductivity, structural stability, and potential use in advanced spintronic applications. In this material, the Ru4+ crystalline field is relatively large compared to the energy governed by the Hund’s rules, thus resulting in a low spin state configuration of the 4d electrons (S=1; 



                  $\mathrm{t}_{2\mathrm{g}}^{4} \mathrm{e}_{\mathrm{g}}^{0}$
                ) [1]. In contrast, Fe4+ ions in SrFeO3 (antiferromagnetic (AF) perovskite oxide with a lattice constant of ∼3.85 Å) exhibit 3d orbital electrons in a high spin state (



                  $\mathrm{t}_{2\mathrm{g}}^{3}\mathrm{e}_{\mathrm{g}}^{1}$
                ) that interact with each other through a G-type antiferromagnetic superexchange coupling (T
                N=134 K) [2]. Therefore, it is reasonable to expect that Fe4+ doping in SRO would result in significant modifications to the magnetic structure and properties of the material depending on the magnetic nature of the competing Fe–O–Fe, Fe–O–Ru, and Ru–O–Ru bonds. In the case of magnetically dilute Fe-doped SRO, electron injection into the eg levels will affect the ferromagnetic superexchange between the Ru ions by disturbing their crystalline field effects and the RuO6 chain angle. Furthermore, we expect that magnetic moments in Fe-doped SRO films could be pinned to interfacial pinning sites (if antiferromagnetically coupled Fe–O–Fe bonding chains were embedded in the host SRO matrix) that require an additional magnetic field to destabilize the pinned state, namely through the magnetic switching fields phenomenon. To the best of our knowledge, the observation of switching fields has never been reported in any transition metal doped SRO film and, in fact, only a couple of publications have so far reported the synthesis of Fe-doped SRO films, but without showing their magnetic switching field [3–5].
